                    <span>I'm not a great conservationist although as a scientist giving talks at public forums and meeting with people professionally and socially I have to be reasonably effective. This is one of three books I purchased to brush up on my conversational skills. I must say this book is a sore disappointment and complete waste of time (never mind money). The book is full of tautologies such as liking people is a great plus, be comfortable in one's own skin, etc. The so-called "advice" in the book reduces the difficulties associated with making good conservation to equally (or more) difficult traits that, if you could easily solve, would transform you into a new person. One gets a strong sense that RoAne and her pals (she lists so many folks in the book, many of whom she interacted with at events where RoAne was a keynote speaker) are the modern equivalent of snake oil merchants, peddling books by padding them with misleading reviews. I have two more books to go, but my recommendation is never to buy a book written by this person again. Unless you can peruse it at an airport bookstore which is what I would typically do for self-help type books. Regrettably not in this instance.</span>
                  
